<h2 id="basics-of-affordable-housing">Basics of affordable housing</h2>
<p>
  <b>Affordable housing</b> (also known as <b>below market rate</b> or <b>BMR</b> housing) is housing that's typically subsidized by one or more external funding sources.  The external funding means a tenant's rent will be lower than the typical area rent levels (i.e. below market rate). Sometimes an entire property is devoted to affordable housing, and sometimes there are only a few BMR units within a market-rate apartment complex.
</p>

<h3 id="income-restrictions">Income restrictions</h3>
<p>
  Nearly all affordable housing is income-restricted.  This means that a household must earn less than a threshold value in order to be eligible to live there.  The threshold value typically depends on the applicant's household size&mdash;larger households can have more income and still be eligible.  The maximum income values (for all household sizes) are usually specified using a shorthand: percent of <b>area median income</b> or <b>AMI</b>.
</p>
<figure>
  <p>
    {% image images.example-hud-ami-table, "png" %}
  </p>
  <figcaption>Example maximum income table for "Low" (80% AMI), "Very Low" (50% AMI), and "Extremely Low" (30% AMI) income levels for Santa Clara county. (<a href="https://www.huduser.gov/portal/datasets/il/il2023/2023summary.odn?states=6.0&data=2023&inputname=METRO41940M41940*0608599999%2BSanta+Clara+County&stname=California&statefp=06&year=2023&selection_type=county" target="_blank">source</a>)</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>
  Unfortunately, there is no single standard for the AMI value for a county, and so maximum income values can vary between properties, even for the same nominal percent AMI.  Common sources for AMI values include the California Tax Credit Allocation Committee (<b>CTCAC</b> or <b>TCAC</b>), the California Department of Housing and Community Development (<b>HCD</b>) and the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (<b>HUD</b>).
</p>
<p>
  In addition to a maximum allowed income, there is also often a <b>minimum income</b> threshold.  This is to ensure that applicants have the financial ability to pay rent.  Usually the minimum yearly income is specified as some multiple of the yearly rent (for example, 2.5 times yearly rent).
</p>

<h3 id="rent">Rent</h3>
<p>
  It is common for rent to change depending on the income bracket of the applicant.  For example, if the applicant has an income under the 30% AMI threshold, their rent will be lower than an applicant who has income under 50% AMI (but above 30% AMI).  Apartment units usually target certain % AMI income brackets.  Thus, a single unit may have multiple rent offerings, one for each income bracket targeted.
</p>

<h3 id="waitlist-status">Waitlist status</h3>
<p>
  Because there are far more low-income households than there are BMR units, there is often a <b>waitlist</b> for affordable housing.  The waitlist usually only opens for a short time.  At all other times, the property does not accept applications.  When apartments become available, the property will select from the waitlist.  Rarely, properties offer available units directly to applicants with no waitlist.
</p>

<h2 id="types-of-property-websites">Types of property websites</h2>
<p>
  For apartment complexes that cater entirely to low-income residents, all the relevant income restrictions, rents, and waitlist status can be found on the property's website.  It is easier to find values for our database on these types of websites.
</p>
