<h4 id="supplemental-websites">Supplemental websites</h4>
<p>
  Some properties have multiple websites associated with them in our database.  All associated websites are listed in the data entry fields, so be sure to explore those supplemental sites too when looking for information.
</p>

<h4 id="wheelchair-icon">Wheelchair Accessibility</h4>
<p>
  Many property websites and documents will include a wheelchair icon.  This does <b>not</b> necessarily mean there exist wheelchair accessible units in that complex.  Often, the icon is used in conjunction with the Equal Housing Opportunity logo to specify that the property does not discriminate on the basis of disability. Properties that offer wheelchair accessible units will often specifically state it using language like "ADA compliant" or "wheelchair accessible."
</p>

<h4 id="conflicting-information">Conflicting information</h4>
<p>
  It is common to find rent and income data in multiple places on a property website.  For example, there could be a maximum income table in the application PDF, the property flyer PDF, and on the webpage itself.  Sometimes, the values are not the same across those documents.  One trick for PDF documents is to look at the URL in the browser address bar to see the filename of the PDF.  Many times, the date it was updated will appear in the filename.  Other times, the revision date will be in the footer of the PDF.  Use the most recent data you can find.
</p>

<h4 id="no-data-available">No data available</h4>
<p>
  The reality is, some property websites simply do not give the information we are looking for.  This is quite common and is not something to worry about.  Just do the best you can!
</p>
